ivate, progressive private school, with, like, six or seven people, kids, in a class - about half would be Jewish. It wasn\rquote t entirely, by any means.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 Going back to your parents, would you say that either your mother or father were easy to talk to?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid12480245\charrsid4223568 Leonore:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 
Certainly not my father. He loved children, and he read aloud to us, and sometimes he would play board games with us. But he just wasn\rquote t there. A great deal of the time he just wasn\rquote t there. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid12480245 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 
My mother was a towering presence, she took motherhood very seriously, and she joined the Child Study Association or something like that. She was on the Book Committees, and she would get all these books before they were published, and bring them back. An
d she would then write reviews on the basis of what we said. And it was wonderful! 
