Helen, who eventually became a Freudian psychoanalyst, after becoming a doctor. But she really ran the show! And I was always trying to keep up. I was second.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 She ran the show in terms of these sort of imaginative games?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid12480245\charrsid4223568 Leonore:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 
Yes, and just generally was in charge. First there was my mother, and then there was Helen. I think, probably we were rather coddled from other children, after we moved to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}New Canaan{\*\xmlclose}. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid12480245 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 
But then during the War, my cousin came to live with us while her father was in the Army \endash  that was my dear Aunt Mary and her daughter \endash  she was between Helen and me, in age, and I loved her very much. We got on really well, because I didn
\rquote t have to figh
t her the way I fought Helen. And she was a gifted pianist, and she used to play, and I would dance. But when she was about 11 she became ill with some intestinal disease, which is now curable with antibiotics, and she just continued ill until she was 18,
 and she died when she was 19. And that was a huge pressure on me, her continued illness. So I always felt guilty, she was going sort of downhill and getting worse and worse, and I was getting bigger and stroppier all the time! 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid12846783 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 
