e was trying. But that inter-War period in the States, and I think here, as well, was very difficult for women. I mean, they were told that, you know, here she was, the wife of a very successful neurosurgeon, with four kids and so on, why did she want any
thing else? But, no, she was fed the whole line.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 But you were brought up to believe that women should go for education?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid12480245\charrsid4223568 Leonore:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 
Certainly for education. And my sister, as I said, went straight into college at 16, she went to Radcliffe, of course, and so she was in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Medical{\*\xmlclose} 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}School{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} by the time she was 20. But, looking back, my father gave us double messages. Definitely. He wanted his daughters to be educated, but what they did with that, he wasn\rquote 
t so sure. His attitude towards some of his female colleagues was ambivalent, and he disliked very much what he called \'93Sonias\'94. A \'93Sonia\'94
 was a woman who wore flat heels, and a bun, and no make-up. So he wanted his daughters also to be very feminine, and we definitely got double messages, which was terribly confusing, I think. But not just from him, but from the teachers and everybody.

\par 
