 course with Richard Myers, called Urban Sociology. He was a lousy teacher! He used to read out of the newspapers! But the topic was very interesting. And we had quite a radical, very young man, who left, because he didn\rquote 
t like Oberlin, he went to a small branch of the University of Michigan, a man called James McKee, who I was very enamoured of. And he taught us about the working-class, and working-class movements and that sort of thing.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid12846783 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
