, the people in the co-ops, the people who were attracted to the co-ops. We set ourselves against what were called \'93The White Shoe Boys\'94, which was a catchphrase for - we didn\rquote t have fraternities, of course, and sororities \endash 
 but they were the nearest thing to it, they were \'93Ra ra\'94
 kind of people, and we were the intellectuals and the radicals. In fact, some kids got kicked out just before their degrees, simply for going to a meeting of some Yugoslavians, or something, in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Cleveland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, and that was at Oberlin, which was much more liberal than most places. But it was a bad time, it was just pre-Civil Riots, it was just before.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid12846783 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
