\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 I\rquote m wondering whether you could start again by saying why you decided to go to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}England{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, and to LSE?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid12662489\charrsid4223568 Leonore:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 Well, it was 1953. I certainly wanted to go on and do graduate work. I didn\rquote 
t look much beyond graduate work, but I knew that I wanted to do that. And I was accepted at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Columbia{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, and I had an inter
view with Robert Merton, which was quite interesting! Well, like, he was very professorial, with tweeds and a pipe, and so on, and rather condescending, but basically very welcoming, in his own way. But all I can remember at the interview was that I wore 
an exceptionally childish outfit that my mother had made, with embroidery on it! Totally unsuitable, in fact! And that\rquote s interesting that that\rquote s all I really remember about it. And I applied to Radcliffe and was not accepted. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid12662489 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 But I knew, because I had dis
covered an LSE catalogue in the Oberlin Library, and I had begun to form this image of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}England{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. The Labour Government had just been in, and it was very exciting, a Socialist government and so on, and I was very disenchanted with the Stat
es then, which was going into the peak of post-War materialism, the veterans coming back home, and so there was a tremendous push for marriage and family \endash 
 having children and so on. Underneath, the Civil Rights Movement was beginning to rumble, but it wasn\rquote 
t even called that. Nobody knew, and so the whole issue of Black America [was] seething, and, of course, at a place like Oberlin, you were more aware of that. But nothing was happening, politically. So there was a terrific political pull, especially towa
rds {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}England{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. And, of course, it was also English-speaking, which made it much easier. And I applied to LSE and was accepted without any problem, and it was extremely inexpensive, compared to an {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
PlaceName}}American{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Graduate{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}School{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, even with the fares. But I think, looking back years and years later, I realised there was a personal element too. I had to get away from this quite powerful family. When I was accepted at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Columbia{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, my parents were delighted, and they said that I could use my father\rquote 
s office, where he had a little sleeping place, where he saw his neuro-surgical patients, that I could live there. And the thought of being so involved in that set-up was actually horrendous! I just fled! And there was al
so my older sister, looking back on it, who had, by that time, finished Medical School and just begun her hospital training, and was married to another very bright, ambitious young doctor. So I think I just wanted to get away. And my brother was already d
oing pre-medical at Harvard. I just felt I just had to get away somewhere quite different. And I had some romantic notions about {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}England{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
! Expected to get off the boat and see hansom cabs! Fog! I certainly saw the fog! So I went by boat. And it will be exactly 50 years, next week, that I landed in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Southampton{\*\xmlclose}.
