t really understand! So there was that side of it. But there was also the more - you felt you were engaged in the wider society, that the LSE was, in a way, a centre of radical politics as well. It wasn\rquote t just academic \endash 
 well, we felt it wasn\rquote t. And the atmosphere,
 a lot of it was from the older returned servicemen, so they were quite serious. In a way, an extension of the older returned servicemen at Oberlin, although of course, in a completely different cultural context. Yeah, Basil Bernstein was there. He
\rquote d been in the RAF for six years, or something like that. And [Asher Tropp] had been in the Navy, I think. And aside from being female, I felt quite young and inexperienced. These were heavies.
