\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 Do you see yourself, now, as both a historian and a sociologist? Or as either one of the two?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1723874\charrsid4223568 Leonore:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 Certainly my recognition has been much more within history circles, that\rquote 
s true. But in the last seven or eight years, I guess you would say, I found myself going back to thinking more conceptually. I\rquote m always, of course, through the Feminist Movement, or Women\rquote 
s Movement, trying to keep up with Feminist Theory, which, in some ways, after the cultural turn, became more and more arid in some ways. But I still think that that - I don\rquote t know whether it\rquote s because it\rquote s a natura
l home, or because that\rquote s the way I started, but that\rquote s what led me to doing the work on }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 The Family Story}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 
, in trying to conceptualise the family and kinship. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1723874 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 
In the last five years or so, David Sabean has been very important to me, because he\rquote s the one w
ho, as a historian, is also very interested in kinship, and, in fact, indeed, in siblings, among other things. His work is just so amazing! And although he takes the role of women very seriously, I think he certainly doesn\rquote 
t come with the same understanding that people that worked in Feminist concepts. We come at these things \endash  at similar problems \endash  in rather different ways, which is not surprising. So I would say, in the last five years or so, I\rquote 
ve moved, again, into a more conceptual, more interdisciplinary \endash  certainly for the sibling project. In fact, it may just fall apart because it\rquote s so interdisciplinary! (LAUGHS) It\rquote 
s not what I would ever advise a graduate student in history to do, I must say. No. No. No.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid12846783 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 Well, I would quite like to ask you one other question, but you can skip it. You\rquote 
ve been living with a famous class sociologist, is there any kind of intellectual interaction going on there?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1723874\charrsid4223568 Leonore:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 Well clearly, I\rquote ve been very aware of class - partly coming from the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place
}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}United States{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and then entering into English society, you can\rquote t not be! I mean, that\rquote s a lot of what }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 The Best Circles}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568  was about, was about class, and a lot about interaction between servants and so on, and household. So at that level, yes. Certainly from b
eing around people who were studying class, very much so. And the whole debate about women and class, and gender and class, has been very important, and it\rquote s very very important. I think you absorb quite a lot by osmosis. But I wouldn\rquote 
t say directly, no.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 And I wonder how far they absorb by osmosis - like the debate on gender and class. Do you think they\rquote 
ve shifted?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1723874\charrsid4223568 Leonore:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 No. Because I think it\rquote 
s impossible. I think the way class has been conceptualised, I think, at one level, John Goldthorpe is absolutely right, you cannot include women \endash  it doesn\rquote t work. But that\rquote s their problem, because they\rquote 
ve come into it at a point where preconceptions have left out, blanked out, certain questions. That whole effort - do you remember the marriage of Marxism a
nd Feminism? Yeah, it is absolutely impossible. And I have thought about that quite a lot now, I think it is impossible, and that\rquote 
s one reason why I would, I think, going way way back, why I should fit into history. I did a little bit of work for John Goldthorpe, in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, he wanted some coding done on some of his survey material, and I couldn\rquote t do it. And looking back on it now, I can see why I couldn\rquote t do it, because you just couldn\rquote t fit these issues in. They had blocked them out.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid12846783 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 Could you explain that a little bit more?
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid12846783 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1723874\charrsid4223568 Leonore:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 Oh, I tried. I did a long piece with my collected essays, which came out in \rquote 95, part of which I wrote in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Australia{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, in which I go into that in great detail. It goes back certainly Marx\rquote s use of traditional economics, that it\rquote 
s conceived in such a way that it is based on the idea of the wage, of monetary value. And, of course, the whole point about gender roles was that women could not be put into that. They couldn\rquote t be conceived in terms o
f being equated with labour value, particularly their role as wives and mothers. They could enter the labour market and they would become workers, and that bit of them could then be used. But the whole force of those ideas about gender is precisely to def
ine men as individual. I mean, the whole basis of individuals, which underlies, also, ideas about class. It\rquote s very very complicated, obviously. But now, some of that was certainly being looked at by political theorists \endash 
 Cal Pateman was very very important in her book, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 The Sexual Contract}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 . But she\rquote 
s a political scientist, and what they weren\rquote t looking at was the economic side of it. And in that piece, I tried to look at both the concept of the market itself, [how it] undercut, you can\rquote t really look at gender in terms of the market, it
\rquote s impossible, I think, basically. You might be able to do it now, with some very fancy footwork. There are Feminist economists, I think, who are trying to do this, but my interest was in the 18}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\super\insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568  and the 19}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \super\insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 
 century, when these concepts began to be used and formulated, in their historical origins, which laid down that intellectual and conceptual framework.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 Well, I suppose the current problem is partly because more women are occupied in paid work, isn\rquote 
t it? But, on the other hand, there\rquote s also a rise in terms of men who are not employed.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1723874\charrsid4223568 Leonore:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 Yeah, but that\rquote s at an empirical level. We\rquote 
re talking about a conceptual level. And this is what people decry, that women are being more and more defined in terms of their occupat
ions, like men, which was a masculine construction anyway. And bit by bit, that part of femininity which existed precisely because it is outside calculation, in Weberian terms, it\rquote 
s precisely that which cannot be estimated rationally. And, of course, the d
ebates about babies, and can you pay for surrogacy and can you buy love? Can you buy children? And, of course, servants and prostitutes cut back across this whole issue. And I think a lot of the problem has been because they look at in the terms you
\rquote ve put it \endash  employment/not employment \endash  but I\rquote 
m talking about a step back from that, in the very way these things are seen in terms of masculinity/femininity and so on. And I got very interested in that whole area, and as I say, I struggled and struggled with th
is piece, and to a certain extent, that was followed by \endash  I wrote the conceptual chapter in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 The Family Story}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 . It didn
\rquote t really work at some levels, and I know I really, I don\rquote t think, have the capacity to work at that level, so I\rquote m quite glad to step back and look at the siblings, which is a little piece of this! (LAUGHS) But I\rquote m glad, I
\rquote m pleased that I had a shot at it, put it that way.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 Anyway, these approaches often open up the whole thing in just another way.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid1723874\charrsid4223568 Leonore:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 In another way, yes. That\rquote s
 a very good way of putting it. Yes. Yes. And also, my brain is tired, you know? (LAUGHS) I don\rquote t want to work at that level any more. I mean, it\rquote s too demanding. No. No.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s20\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid12846783 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid12846783\charrsid4223568 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
